C++ CAST examples

1)	static_cast

casting happens during compilation.
If casting is not possible, compiler error will be thrown.

	class	Parent					{};
	class	Child: public Parent 	{};
	class	Unrelated				{};

	Child	a;
	Parent	*b	=	&a;			//implicit UPCAST 		OK
	Child	*c	=	&b;			//implicit DOWNCAST 	NOT OK
	
	Child	*d	=	static_cast<Child *>(b);	//Explicit DOWNCAST		OK

	Unrelated *e	=	static_cast<Unrelated *>(&a);	//Explicit conversion 	NO!
															//compiler will throw error


	static_cast	will allow us to make simple conversions between related data types or classes
					will allow us to make UPCAST and DOWNCAST on a hierarchy of classes we are familiar with
					will prevent cast between unrelated class hierarchies

2)	dynamic_cast

casting happens during run time, not during compilation
program may compile, but dynamic cast may FAIL at run time.

you need to detect in you code architecture, whether the dynamic cast will be handled properly 
	and not fail during run time.
will only work will polymorphic instance, meaning we will be dealing with subtype polymorphism, 
	at least 1 virtual member function.
	i.e. 	public: virtual ~Parent( void ) {}
	It activates something called RTTI - RuntTime Type Info, this is hidden from you, allowing Dynamic cast
	to check if it is possible to cast the object with dynamic cast.

will only work on Pointer and Reference.
	1) Child * c	= dynamic_Cast<Child *>(b);	// return address or NULL if conversion is not possible

	2) Child & d = dynamic_Cast<Child &>(*b);	//reference to unreferencing

std::bad_cast	to catch bad cast exception

3)	const_cast

const_cast 	will replace the semantics of c cast in c++

You don't want to do const_cast unless it is really necessary.

	int	a = 42;

	int	const	*b	= &a;					// Implicit promotion	OK		why? const b is immutable, a is mutable

	int	*c	= b;							// Implicit demotion 	NOT OK	why? you can't cast mutable to immutable

	int	*d	= const_cast<int *>(b);		// Explicit demotion	OK
